@NODE "intro" "GummiSurf - Introduction"
@PREV "main"
@NEXT "req"

 @{b}@{u}Introduction@{uu}@{ub}

 GummiSurf started out as a companion tool for the great download manager Charon (by Andrija Antonijevic).
 The latest release has also support for the built-in managers in IBrowse, Sputnik, Voyager and AWeb aswell.

 The main usage is to easy generate a download-list for a download manager if you have a web page
 that contains lets say a lot of pictures of some kind (or any other files aswell).
 Lets say that there are a gallery containing 20 pages with 10 pictures on each page
 and their position is the same path on every page. If we are lucky the names of the pictures
 are "Pic001.jpg", "Pic002.jpg" and up to "Pic200.jpg".

 This is where GummiSurf is very handy since if we know the first and the last place we
 can easy generate a download-list for the download manager without add every single file manualy.


 Q : Why is it called GummiSurf ?

 A : It was a silly working name that was supposed to be changed but I didn't have any better
     name suggested so it's still called this. It's more fun if you know swedish btw. :)
     It was actually called GummiSmurf first, but... nahh =)


@ENDNODE

@NODE "req" "GummiSurf - Requirements"
@PREV "intro"
@NEXT "usage"

 @{b}@{u}Requirements@{uu}@{ub}

 This program needs following stuff:

 · MorphOS 1.x or AmigaOS 4.x
 · MUI

 · And last but not least a download manager such as :
   Charon  - http://www.bigfoot.com/~TheAntony/Charon/

   Now also supporting the built-in managers with IBrowse, Voyager or AWeb.
   Well, GummiSurf can be started and used without it, but has very little point then =)


 This program has been tested on following systems with success:
 bPlan-Pegasos (MorphOS 2.2), AmigaOne (AmigaOS 4.1)

 Tested with following software :
 
 * Charon 1.98
 * IBrowse 2.4
 * Voyager 3.3.127 (PPC)
 * AWeb 3.4 APL (68k and PPC)
          

@ENDNODE

@NODE "usage" "GummiSurf - Usage"
@PREV "req"
@NEXT "faq"

 @{b}@{u}Usage@{uu}@{ub}

 The GUI is pretty self explaining, but here are follows some further
 information about the objects in the window.

 @{b}Base URL@{ub}
 Here you defines the base URL for the place where the files you intend to
 download is placed. There is a good example at the amiga.org-website
 Here is a lot of pictures that can be found at :

 http://amiga.org/modules/myalbum/photos/1.jpg
 http://amiga.org/modules/myalbum/photos/2.jpg

 And the number goes beyond 500 as far as I know.

 So if we would like to download the pictures we set the base URL to :
 http://amiga.org/modules/myalbum/photos/
 
 @{b}Base Name@{ub}
 If we continues with the URL above we see that there is no base name, just
 numbers so we left this field blank.
 Use this field incase the name is "Picture1.jpg" or similar.
 If this would be the case enter "Picture" in this field.

 @{b}Extension@{ub}
 The extension for the pictures above is ".jpg" and that is what we enter
 in this field.

 @{b}Save Path@{ub}
 This is where you want the download manager to save your files.
 If this is left blank it uses its default path instead.
 You can choose this by pressing the button beside this field aswell (easier).

 @{i}Notice : When using GummiSurf with IBrowse and Voyager this field is not used at all
          since the programs currently don't have any options for it.@{ui}


 @{b}From@{ub}
 Here you enter the first number in a row of the files you want to download
 If we want to start to download from picture 10, we enter "10" in this field.

 @{b}To@{ub}
 Here you enter the last number in the download serie, so if we want to download
 up to picture 50, just enter "50" in this field.

 @{b}Digits@{ub}
 Here you can force the name to always contain a fixed number of digits,
 if we enter "3" in this field the name download name will be filled with zeros
 until it's "enough". So if we have entered "1" in the @{b}From@{ub}-field and
 "3" in this field, the name to download will be sat to "003.jpg" instead of just "3.jpg"
 If you don't want to use this option, set the slider to "1".

 @{b}Preview@{ub}
 This is a preview of the first "object" that is going to be generated with GummiSurf.
 The preview is changed directly when you edit any of the fields in the GUI.
 And not only is it a preview string, you can actually click on it and if you
 have configured OpenURL (needs openurl.library) to point at your favourite browser,
 the link will be seen there.


=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=

 @{b}Generate file@{ub}
 Here you can generate a file of one of following choices :
 
 * Charon list - Generates a download-list that can be imported in Charon.
 * HTML list   - A HTML-file which contains the whole generated list.
 * Plain text  - Same as above, just as a plain textfile.


 @{b}Generate to >>@{ub}
 Will generate the filelist on the fly by communicating to one of the 
 following (running) programs :

 * Charon
 * IBrowse
 * Voyager
 * AWeb

 @{i}Notice : When the IBrowse and Voyager choice is used, the save path choosen
          above isn't used because of lack of support of this in the ARexx-API
          in the programs. So it's up to the user itself to pick the proper download-
          directory within the browser.

          Another good idea is to turn on automatical download to save numerous
          hits on the requester =)@{ui}


 @{b}Quit@{ub}
 Doesn't need that much explaining I hope =)

=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=<>=

@{b}ARexx-commands@{ub}

SET_URL
SET_NAME
SET_EXT
SET_PATH
SET_FROM
SET_TO
SET_DIGITS

Let's say you want to change the Base URL to : http://amigaworld.net/modules/myalbum/photos/
While running GummiSurf, you use the following command (either in shell or modify it for a script)

rx "OPTIONS RESULTS; ADDRESS GUMMISURF.1; 'SET_URL http://amigaworld.net/modules/myalbum/photos/';

And you can change every other field like that using any of the other commands aswell.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "faq" "GummiSurf - FAQ"
@PREV "usage"
@NEXT "news"

@{b}@{u}FAQ - Frequently Asked Question@{uu}@{ub}

* @{b}Q = Question@{ub}
* @{b}A = Answer@{ub}

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Q - Where is the AROS-version ?

A - Since I have some sort of limited spare time, the support for these
    isn't dropped, I just havn't had time to compile and test it yet.
    But don't feel that I ignore you, my intention is to support all
    flavours om Amiga-systems around. So just have a little patience =)

------------------------------------------------------------------------------ 
Q - Why doesn't you support WallGet, Sputnik, OWB, NetSurf etc. ?

A - I do that, but the main problem is that the applications doesn't have
    the needed ARexx-command setup or isn't ready for the job yet.
    I'm in contact with the authors of these application and I fully intend
    to support all of them as soon as they add the needed stuff to it =)

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Q - Why has the tooltypes support been removed in this version ?

A - Since I hardly think that it's needed anymore really since the program
    stores the last setup and re-uses it on the next start.
    If someone still think that tooltypes really is needed, please let me
    know and I'll add it again.
    Another reason for removing the tooltypes is the addition of ARexx-
    commands.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@ENDNODE

@NODE "news" "GummiSurf - What's new?"
@PREV "faq"
@NEXT "history"

 @{b}@{u}What's new@{uu}@{ub}

 · Added AmigaOS3 binaries
 · Support for OWB (MorphOS) and NetSurf (OS4)
 · Changed the default URL to a working one =)


@ENDNODE

@NODE "history" "GummiSurf - History"
@PREV "news"
@NEXT "future"

 @{b}@{u}History@{uu}@{ub}

 · 19-10-2009 - Fifth public release (1.4).
              · Added AmigaOS3 binaries
              · Support for OWB (MorphOS) and NetSurf (OS4)
              · Changed the default URL to a working one =)

 · 21-01-2009 - Fourth public release (1.3).
              · Ported the source from AmigaE to C.
              · Both MorphOS (PPC) and AmigaOS (PPC) binaries supplied.
              · Preview of the download URL (make use of openurl.library so you can click on it aswell).
              · Removed the Tooltype support (redundant).
              · ARexx-port enabled with some commands...

 · 19-06-2003 - Third public release (1.2).
              · Supports the built-in download managers in all browsers.
              · Can now also export HTML and Plain text-lists.

 · 09-04-2003 - Second public release (1.1).
              · Added support for Tooltype settings.
              · Fixed the URL-completer so it works even if the user havn't pressed the enter-key.

 · 20-02-2003 - First public release (1.0).


@ENDNODE

